## **Section 2: Product Description**

* **Project Title**: Bobo the Beaver  
    
* **Abstract**: Beavers play a crucial role as ecological engineers, improving water quality, biodiversity, and climate resilience. However, public awareness of their impact remains limited, and they are sometimes treated as pests. Furthermore, unlike traditional methods, like reading or watching videos, this game aims to reach a broader audience by being an interactive learning environment. Although many educational games exist, not many exist that inform people of beavers. We aim to produce a game to fill that space, which will improve public perception of beavers. This project presents an interactive educational game designed to teach players about beavers and their habitats through engaging gameplay. Unlike passive learning methods, the game fosters active participation, making ecological education more accessible and enjoyable. By combining entertainment with education, this game provides an understanding of beavers' vital role in wildlife ecosystems.


* **Goal:** Our project will create an educational game which seeks to teach the user/player about beavers through game mechanics, story, and flavor text. This will not only be about entertaining the player but also sourced, educational content through playing the game. The game will follow similar principles to games made by companies like Brainpop and Leapfrog. We’d be developing this game for a general audience, potentially mimicking the style of edutainment games we grew up with, but with a heavier focus on educational content about beavers and their impact on the environment.   
    
* **Current Practice:** The traditional way people learn about beavers is through reading, class activities, videos, or other class content. Most of these mediums are static, meaning there’s no way for the student/learner to connect and control the content they are consuming. In what few educational games that currently exist, many of them are for-profit, short, outdated, or unsubstantial. The majority of these games are also geared towards teaching younger children math and reading skills, as to more complex topics, ideas, or information.  
    
* **Novelty:** Compared to traditional education content, our game would reach people beyond the normal audience who would want to learn about beavers. While existing educational games like Me: A Kid's Diary tend to be simple web-based games, our game is unique because it will be a fully-fledged 2d game.  Furthermore, these games struggle to balance education and entertainment.  Our game will overcome this by including educational content in both the mechanics and the story.  The game is geared to be entertaining without the educational content, so someone may play the game for fun and end up becoming interested in learning more about beavers and the environment.  
    
* **Effects:** Our game will give users an informative and entertaining way to understand more about the pond and river wildlife ecosystems, emphasizing the impact beavers have on the environment. The game will also educate players on the significance of wetlands, fostering environmental awareness and motivating them to take action in preserving wetlands and beaver habitats.   
    
* **Technical Approach**: We will use the Godot game engine for the majority of this project.  We will use GitHub as our version control system.  Sound design and music creation will be done using FL Studio as a Digital Audio Workstation.  Pixilart.com will be used for the creation of visual assets for the game.   
    
* **Risks:**  Many of us are completely new to Godot and game development in its entirety.  To be successful, we will need to adequately learn both the software and the discipline.  To mitigate this risk, our experienced members will help the less experienced members.  Furthermore, they will include resources (online teaching for the tools we will be using) to ensure everyone is ready.

## **Section 5: Use Cases**

**Ryan’s Use Case: Loading a Minigame**

1. Actors: A user of the game  
2. Trigger: They enter a minigame loading zone  
3. Pre-conditions: They have booted the game, traversed the main map, and moved to a minigame loading zone.  
4. Post-conditions (success scenario): They enter the minigame which loads its assets and they can begin playing the minigame.   
5. Main Success Scenario: The player moves their character on the main map into the minigame loading zone. The program will load in the assets. The program will code for the minigame. The minigame will start.   
6. Extensions/Variations (Alternative Scenarios): They can win the minigame, which will prompt them to leave the minigame and give them a reward for doing so. They can also lose the minigame, which will prompt them to try the minigame again.   
7. Exceptions (Failure Scenario): The game fails to load any/all of the assets, the code does not process minigame logic correctly, the game does not load into the minigame, the game crashes when the minigame is loaded. 

**Grant’s Use Case: Accessing and Changing Settings**

1. Actor: A player that would like to adjust the game settings.  
2. Triggers: The player selects “Settings” from the main menu.  
3. Pre-conditions: The player must be on a main menu, that includes the “Settings” button.  
4. Post-conditions: The player will be taken to the settings menu and can adjust the sound and resolution.  
5. Main Success Scenario — Accessing Settings:   
   1. The player launches the game.  
   2. The player loads into the main menu.  
   3. The player clicks on the “settings” button.  
   4. The player makes any changes to the settings as necessary.  
   5. The player exits back to the main menu.  
6. Extensions/Variations (Alternative Scenarios):   
   1. The player is in game and wants to change a given setting.  
      1. They exit the game to the main menu by pressing escape, then quit.  
      2. They access the settings as described after step b. In the main success scenario.   
7. Exceptions (Failure Scenarios):  
   1. The player is unable to find or access the settings menu.  
   2. The settings menu doesn’t load the settings data.  
   3. The player’s settings changes are not saved. 

**Mia’s Use Case: Reloading A Saved Game**

1. Actors: A player that is returning to a game they had previously started.  
2. Triggers: The player selects “Load Game” in the main menu.  
3. Pre-conditions: The player has to have previously started a new game, made progress or moved around in the game, and then exited the game. This must all be done on the same device.  
4. Post-conditions: The player is able to continue playing their previously started game, and all of their progress has been saved.  
5. Main Success Scenario:  
   1. The player has started up the Bobo the Beaver game on their device.  
   2. The player selects “Load Game” from the main menu.  
   3. The player is taken back to their last saved location on the map with their inventory saved.   
6. Extensions/Variations (Alternative Scenarios):  
   1. The player has never played Bobo the Beaver before, so they select “New Game” from the main menu.  
   2. The player has played the game before but would like to restart, so they select “New Game” from the main menu.  
7. Exceptions (Failure Scenarios):  
1. The player accidentally selects “New Game” instead of “Load Game” from the main menu, erasing all data and progress from their previous game.  
2. The “Load Game” button does not load the player’s previous game and progress.

**Guillermo’s Use Case:  Submitting Feedback in the Game**

1. Actor: Player (Person who plays the game)  
2. Trigger: The player wants to provide feedback about their experience with the game.  
3. Pre-conditions:  
   1. The player has installed and launched the game.  
   2. The player has completed some gameplay or encountered an issue.  
4. Post-conditions:  
   1. The player successfully submits their feedback through the game's built-in feedback system.  
   2. The feedback is stored and sent to the developers for review.  
5. Main Success Scenario:  
   1. The player navigates to the game's main menu and selects the "Submit Feedback" option.  
   2. The player types their feedback into the provided text box.  
   3. The player clicks the "Submit" button.  
   4. The game displays a confirmation message: "Thank you for your feedback\!"  
   5. The game internally stores and sends the feedback to the developer’s system.  
6. Extensions/Variations (Alternative Scenarios):  
   1. The player chooses to submit feedback anonymously by not entering personal details.  
   2. The player attaches a screenshot or in-game log to help developers understand the issue.  
   3. The game provides an optional survey after submitting feedback to gather more insights.  
7. Exceptions (Failure Scenarios):  
   1. The feedback form fails to load, and the player is shown an error message.  
   2. The submission fails due to internet connectivity issues, prompting the player to try again later.  
   3. The player exits the feedback form without submitting, and no data is sent.

**Mike’s Use Case: Updating the Inventory**

1. Actor: A player that has completed a minigame.  
2. Triggers: The player has successfully won a minigame.  
3. Pre-conditions: The player has started and successfully completed a minigame.  
4. Post-conditions: The player has received either a log or a rock for completing the minigame, and it can be found in their inventory.  
5. Main Success Scenario:   
   1. The player finds a minigame on the map and begins playing the game.  
   2. The player successfully completes the minigame.  
   3. The player clicks on the beaver lodge on the bottom of their screen, and the new item should appear in their inventory.  
6. Extensions/Variations (Alternative Scenarios):  
   1. The player does not successfully find or complete any of the minigames.  
   2. The player completes a minigame more than four times, so no new items appear in their inventory, as the maximum items per game is four.   
7. Exceptions (Failure Scenarios):   
   1. The game fails to reward the player with a new inventory item after completing a minigame.  
   2. The player is unaware that they are being awarded new inventory items after winning a minigame.

## **Section 8: Software Architecture**

This project is an Event Driven Architecture (EDA).  The various scenes within the Godot engine will serve as event listeners and event emitters to support this architecture.  The benefit of this architecture is that it allows modularity and stability within what seems like a singular program environment.  The following describes the function of these scenes and how they interact with each other. 

![][image1]

### **Major Software Components:**

* **Game Manager**: The game manager will be a centralized object that loads in first before anything else within the game. It will be responsible for variables, methods, and objects that are important to keep track of independently of which scene the player is in. It’s also used to manage game systems such as file saving and loading, player location, scene management, etc.  
  * **Interfaces**: Traversable map, inventory, minigames, NPCs, Objects, All UI systems,   
  * **Data**: Player save file, NPC save files, in game time, inventory objects, story process, player location data, NPC movement, scene management data  
  * **Assumptions**: Assumes that each individual component has methods to communicate data back to game manager and methods to receive data from game manager

* **Player instance**: The in-game player object is moved in game by the player in order to traverse and interact with the game world. When a player gives input data such as keyboard inputs, the game responds accordingly by moving and acting on the player object.   
  * **Interfaces**: Game manager, traversable map, inventory, interactable NPC’s, minigames, interactable objects  
  * **Data**: Player x coordinate, player y coordinate, speed, sprite, and collision shape.  
  * **Assumptions**: The player instance should be spawned only inside of a game scene. 

* **Game Scene**: This contains all the visual and functional game elements.  It will either be the main map or the minigames.    
  * **Interfaces**: Player instance, game manager.  
  * **Data**: Tilemap or background sprites depending on scene, boundary nodes, NPC nodes and scripting, audio streams  
  * **Assumptions**: Assumes that the game manager has successfully called the given game scene to load using the scene loader object. 

### **Decision Alternatives:**

**Static Traversable Map**

* **Pros**:   
  * Simpler to implement, as the map doesn't change dynamically.   
    * Easier to test and debug.  
  * **Cons**:   
    * Limits replayability, as players cannot explore new areas or experience the environment changing based on their progress.

**Local Multiplayer Mode**

* **Pros**:   
  * No internet access required   
    * Easier to test and debug.  
    * Lower latency  
  * **Cons**:   
    * Not ideal for situations where players cannot easily sit around the same screen, like at a large event or for remote play  
    * Games with split-screen or shared screen need to be carefully designed to ensure that everyone can see and interact with the game properly.

## **Section 9: Software Design**

### **UI Design**

* Main Menu UI: Designed to allow the player to start a new game, load a previous game, access the settings and feedback form, and also close the game. Styled to match the design and story of the game. 

### **![][image2]**

* NPC Interaction UI: Designed to communicate important information about the game and beavers to the player in a clear and easily readable way. Includes the NPC image to clearly show who the player is communicating with, and includes a next button to allow the player to move on to the next message. Stylized to match the design and other sprites in the game.

![][image3]

* Mini Map UI: Designed to allow players to see where they are located on the main map to help them navigate to different locations. 

![][image4]

* Inventory UI: Designed to allow players to visually see the different objects they’ve collected from completing minigames, and helps players identify which objects they are still missing. It also informs players on what materials beavers use to build dams, and is stylized to match the rest of the game design. 

![][image5]

* Feedback UI: Designed to allow players to easily submit feedback to the developers. Stylized to match the design of other menus and sprites.

![][image6]

### **Software Component Responsibilities / Units of Abstraction**

* **Game Manager**: The game manager will be a 2D node scene. It’s the highest level of abstraction, taking care of higher order functions, variables, and components of the game. It will be responsible for keeping track of data that’s independent of specific scenes, and used to load and unload different scenes/instances. 

* **Player Instance**: The player instance will be part of a few classes, including “Pauseable” which covers objects that may be paused, and “GameComponents” which covers objects and classes that send data to the game manager.  It is responsible for telling the game manager when it changes positions or attempts to interact with a map element.   
    
* **Game Scene:** The Game scene is responsible for loading visual components.  It will include an instance of the player and many instances of the various scene elements to create the playable map area.   
    
* **Save / Settings Files:** The save and settings files are responsible for keeping track of important game variables and settings values, respectively.

## **Section 11: Team Process Description**

### **Software Tool Set Justification:** 

Godot: Godot will be the primary tool used for our game development. Godot is a fantastic tool for game development as it’s open-source, routinely updated, and has a wide community of support. The built in IDE makes it easy for our programmers to work on the project. Godot is not resource intensive which means it’s compatible with all of our machines. It also supports cross-platform development so that we can work with windows and apple computers. Lastly Godot is distributed under the MIT license which allows us to produce games and distribute them as long as we attribute Godot as the engine. 

Github: We will be using Github for our version control system. We are choosing it not only because it’s a requirement for class but also because it has great integration with Godot. Godot has built in version control with Git, and thus it was easy to set up our repository with very few extra steps. 

Discord: Discord is an accessible communication program because creating an account and server is free.  It is effective at splitting topics into various text channels, which will help us differentiate between important aspects of our team work.  

FL Studio: This is a Digital Audio Workstation that all music and sound design for the game will be conducted in.  Grant already has a full license for this software and several years of experience using it, so it makes sense to take advantage of the resource.  Furthermore, FL Studio has a free, unlimited trial version that is accessible to other group members if they need to access it.  

Pixilart: Pixilart is an online drawing editor that will be used to make the visual content for our game. It is free to use and accessible through any web browser, and has complimentary apps on Google Play and the App Store for both iOS and Android. It is a robust and in-depth editor that allows our group to create objects, backdrops, and sprites that make up the visual medium of our game. Being free and accessible to all group members makes it a good tool for our visual design.

### **Risk Assessment:**

* The data and data-parsing isn’t standardized among different parts of the project  
  * Medium  
  * Medium  
  * We are working on many different parts of the code asynchronously, which allows us to work faster but may cause us to implement the data storage and parsing multiple different ways. This means the likelihood of it occurring is moderate, and the impact is based on Mike’s experience in other games, where it could crash the game.   
  * To reduce the likelihood of this occurring, we have made a guide on how to implement things like data storage and data-parsing, which when followed will standardize how we interact with data. We can review each other's code regularly in order to verify our data interactions are consistent.  
  * By creating a piece of data with one data storage mechanism, we can give it to each data-interacting piece in the project to see if it works the same way. This will show if it parses the same way, which will also imply it creates it the same way.   
  * We would have to remove the way one person implemented data interacting, and completely replace it with another. We would default to using Mike’s methods, as he is the head dev.   
* When merging to our git repository, we may have merge conflicts that break the project  
  * Medium  
  * Low  
  * We are basing this estimate off of our previous experience with git, where we think it is possible that one of our group members could introduce a bad merge.  
  * To reduce the impact, we will commit often, so if a merge conflict does happen, not much information will be lost when we revert.   
  * We could implement a CI that tests if any merge causes problems to the project by failing the unit tests we created.   
  * We can use git to revert to an earlier commit, and take more care into merging and combining. This could mean some data is lost, or lead to a much more time-consuming merge process.   
* Godot 4.3 has several compatibility issues with Godot Unit Test (GUT), which would stop us from creating necessary tests.  Testing is essential to the project, so this would be a severe inhibitor.   
  * Medium  
  * Medium  
  * We estimated this risk based on our knowledge of existing issues with compatibility.  An example is that Godot 4.0 had a method for scene initialization called instance(), but this was changed in Godot 4.3 to instantiate().  The current version of GUT is compatible with the instance() method, but not the instantiate() method.  There is a risk that this and any other incompatible methods could inhibit our ability to create adequate unit tests.  Since testing is a required part of a project and essential to ensuring safe functionality of new code, it could be detrimental to our completion of the project.  
  * We can reduce the impact of this risk by designing our tests to create objects by using the new() method on the script attached to the appropriate scene.  
  *  While creating tests, we will implement GUT testing into our continuous integration, so it will automatically let us know that the test suite has failed.  This will also email the developer who made the commit / pull request.    
  * To mitigate this risk should it occur, we will have to use the other existing Godot testing software, such as Godot Tester.  However, this would not be ideal because the quality and documentation on the alternatives is worse than GUT.    
* Integration between minigames and the main map fail, leading to minigames/main-map being inaccessible  
  * Low  
  * High  
  * We are basing this estimate off the fact that minigames with a main map are essential to the idea of the game, and would have to be resolved before the project is done. The low likelihood is due to this a very noticeable bug, which we could likely fix with effort.   
  * To reduce the impact of this happening, we can make sure the minigames do not rely on the main-map and vice versa, so if one fails the other can still work.   
  * To test this, we can write unit tests that test the interactions between the main-map and minigame instances, as well as do playtesting of the game to make sure that it works.   
  * We would have to remove the main map from the game, and solely tell the game through the minigames, which would greatly impact the final quality of our game.   
* Miscommunication among team members could lead to different members creating different things, and it comes out as a mismatch at the end.  
  * Low likelihood of occurring  
  * Medium impact if it occurs   
  * We are basing this estimate on our current communication of our progress and weekly goals.   
  * Sharing our weekly updates, prevents group members from clashing on design aspects. We also have a color palette and style guide to ensure all members are on the same page. These weekly updates also help to evaluate how close our perceptions of each part of the project are.   
  * Regular showcases of designs and implementation throughout the process, so each other member will immediately know their ideas match. This will identify the problems earlier than just comparing final drafts.  
  * There will be a meeting between all impacted members, where they work out the details on exactly what they are making. This would slow the project, and may require cutting some smaller features. 

### **Test Plan & Bugs**

**Specific Aspects to Test**  
Game mechanics are at the core of the game’s experience. We will test features such as player movement, inventory management, NPC interactions, and mini-games. These elements form the backbone of the game and are essential for ensuring that the gameplay functions as intended. For educational content, we will verify that the beaver-related facts are accurate.

UI testing will be another aspect. We will ensure that the user interface is intuitive and easy to navigate, with clear menus, buttons, and transitions between screens. We will check that all visual elements, such as text, icons, and images, are displayed correctly, and that the game’s menus and controls are responsive and functional.

We will also test sound and music. It is important to verify that sound effects and music play correctly at appropriate times during gameplay. This includes ensuring that the audio cues function during the player’s experience, such as environmental sounds, interactions, or background music.

Additionally, we will test the save/load system to make sure that players’ progress is preserved. This includes verifying that when a player saves and exits the game, their location, inventory, and other game data persist when the game is loaded again.

Finally, the multiplayer aspect will be another focus. We will test the synchronization of player actions across different devices to ensure that movements and interactions are consistently reflected in real-time. This will include verifying that server-client communication is functioning correctly, and that the game experience remains smooth for all players involved.

**Test Strategy**  
To test these aspects, we will follow a structured process. First, we will create a test plan using Trello. This will help us organize and keep track of what needs to be tested. We will break testing into smaller, manageable tasks, such as testing player movement or NPC dialogue one at a time to ensure each part works as expected.

For unit testing, we will test each part of the game separately manually and, if time allows, with test automation scripts to make testing faster and more reliable. For example, we’ll check if the player moves correctly when pressing keys like WASD. We’ll also test the inventory system to make sure items can be added, removed, and shown properly. We’ll check NPC interactions to ensure that dialogue boxes appear when talking to NPCs and that the content is displayed correctly

Once these parts pass their individual tests, we’ll do system testing to make sure everything works well together. For example, we’ll test the save/load system to make sure player progress, like inventory and location, is saved properly. We’ll also test multiplayer to make sure players’ movements and actions match up on different devices. Additionally, we’ll test the menus and how the game moves between different screens to ensure smooth transitions.

For play testing, we’ll have real users try the game to see if it’s easy to understand and navigate. We’ll get feedback on how simple it is to learn the controls, move through menus, and enjoy the educational content. We’ll also test features like resizing text and high-contrast text to make sure the game is accessible to everyone. Furthermore, we’ll watch how players interact with the educational content to see if they’re learning and if the game encourages them to keep playing.

Finally, we will share test results through Discord and track any bugs we find on GitHub Issues. We’ll categorize each bug (like UI problems, multiplayer issues, or sound bugs) and describe how to reproduce it. We’ll also use Trello to assign tasks and prioritize fixing bugs or making improvements based on the results of our tests. By following this process, we’ll make sure the game works well and is fun and educational for players.

**CI Test-Automation**

Our test-automation infrastructure is GUT 9.3.1 (Godot Unit Test).

We decided to use GUT because it is the only Unit Testing software we could find that was (mostly) compatible with Godot 4.3.  It ended up being a good choice because there are compatibility options with GitHub Actions.  

For new tests, you create a .gd file in either the res://test/unit folder or res://test/integration folder. The filename must begin with “test\_” or GUT will not run the test. These tests will be written by extending GutTest, and will be written using GUT test design. Each test function must be started test\_, or else it will not be counted as a test in GUT. More information about writing GUT tests can be seen here https://gut.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Quick-Start.html\#creating-tests.

We are using GitHub Actions to control our Continuous Integration.  Our project is linked to it through the GitHub Actions tab, which automatically triggers whenever a Push / Pull Request happens.  

We chose GitHub Actions to control our CI because there are several GitHub Actions marketplace options for incorporating GUT, building release binaries, and release creation.  These particular operations needed to be compatible with Godot and GUT, so GitHub Actions was the most well-documented version.  Furthermore, GitHub Actions is incorporated into GitHub by default, so we do not have to go through the effort of using an external application.  

|  | GitHub Actions | GitLab | Agola |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Pros | There are a lot of options and variety in the actions marketplace. Well documented, and compatible with GUT | Does not require third party integration in order to test software. Used by several leaders of industry for a large variety of projects. Boosts privacy-first AI, significantly faster cycle time, and robust security features  | Allows users to easily test runs in different environments without having to change the setup each time. It’s easy to integrate with GitHub and it’s runs are saved in the repositories and will automatically run whenever a new push and pull request is made. |
| Cons | Most of those are outdated and rely on a tux family library, which is no longer up.  | Very little documentation about integrating GitLab with Godot, or resources on learning how to integrate. The compute minutes and member cap is far smaller than Github actions. | There is very little documentation on integrating it with Godot.  |

As of now, we are executing 8 unit tests in each CI build.  One test\_test is a dummy test to ensure that GUT is working properly.  test\_player\_demo is a test script which ensures that the player\_demo gets created correctly when initializing the GameManager object.  It then tests player movement functionality as well.  test\_volume\_slider is a script which creates a dummy volume slide and links it to the master audio bus.  It then tests whether changing the slider value correspondingly changes the master audio bus volume.  The other tests include a variety of game features such as the map boundaries, the feedback UI, the player movement audio, and the swimming minigame audio.

The CI build is triggered by and Push / Pull request to the main branch of the repository.

# **Section 12: Reflections** 

**Grant Pasquantonio**   
One thing that worked exceptionally well is our specialization into our development roles.  Each of us selected a part of the project to focus on.  We were then able to share that knowledge with the rest of the group.  Whenever someone had a problem in a given subject, they could get help from the “domain expert” of the group.  This helped us break up a large project into smaller, digestible parts.  As such, I learned that delegation of software development tasks is an effective strategy.  

Something we could have done differently with our planning is the allocation of the minigames.  We created ideas for minigames in the planning phase, but we didn’t assign developers / teams to the minigames until late in the implementation phase.  The result of this was that we were unable to finish two of the planned minigames.  As such, the lesson that I learned from this is that every discrete task that is known in the planning phase should have at least one developer assigned to it.  This will ensure that, even if the developer ends up being unable to work on that task, they will be responsible for ensuring that the work is reassigned to someone else who has time to complete the task.  

As for execution, one thing we could have improved upon was our file management within the project directory.  We had several instances where a component that a given member was working on had dependency issues when being combined with the main project.  Fixing these dependencies costed us a decent amount of time.  To mitigate this in the future, we should establish a clear file organization in the planning phase.  Furthermore, developers should work within the planned directory structure even if they are working in their own branches.  Overall, the lesson that I learned from dealing with these dependency issues that it is important that every member of the team upholds file management best practices throughout the project. This is because even one dependency issue early on can cause many more problems later.  

**Mike Nunzio**  
Working on Bobo The Beaver taught me an incredible amount about software development from every angle. It made me a better game designer, taught me an incredible amount about Godot, introduced me to continuous integration and so much more. In previous game projects I never really had a centralized object to keep track of everything, it was mostly a couple of files and some logic in the central game loop. They showed me a lot of features and aspects of Godot that I had never done before, such as creating and submitting forms, Godot unit testing, tile mapping, audio emitters, and so much more. I think my largest take away would be just how important proper design and documentation is to team success. There were areas where my documentation could have been stronger and that would have saved us some time and confusion. When the documentation was well done, it made for such a better and faster experience.

Lastly I think I learned a lot about management, both personally and as a group. I had never worked on a project before that had so many moving parts and different people writing code. It was a little bit intimidating at first, but by the end I was a lot more comfortable working with the team. All and all, this game was probably the most polished piece of software I’ve made for a class before. We finished a lot of what we set out to accomplish and despite some setbacks, we were able to push through all the same. I hope that we could eventually return to the project once we have more free time or motivation to work on it. I’m very proud of what we’ve done\!
